english:
  title: Doubts Concerning the Classic of Mountains and Seas
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I read the Classic of Mountains and Seas, each scroll bears the inscription: 'Compiled by the Great Yu, transmitted by Guo Ce.' This would suggest the work was authored by Yu of Xia. Yet I doubt this to be true. Why? The ancients said: 'A son conceals his father's faults, a father conceals his son's.' The Analects records: 'When the father stole a sheep, the son bore witness against him'—a thing condemned. When Confucius compiled the Spring and Autumn Annals, though he wrote with a direct brush, he treated Lu as his ancestral state and concealed all great evils, refusing to record them. If the Classic of Mountains and Seas were truly Yu's work, would he not conceal his father's great shame? Yet in the Northeast Chronicle it states: 'When the flood reached heaven, Gun stole the Emperor's sacred soil to dam the waters. The Emperor commanded Zhurong to slay Gun at Feather Field.' Gun was Yu's father—surely such a matter should not be recorded. If it must be recorded as fact, could it not say Gun 'took' rather than 'stole' the Emperor's soil? This would not violate propriety.

    I have examined the Memorial on Presenting the Classics, which says: 'When the great flood once inundated all things, Gun's efforts bore no fruit. Yao then commanded Yu to inherit the task. Bo Yi and Bo Yue drove the beasts and divided water from earth, recording their strange wonders. They classified creatures and their natures, composing the Classic of Mountains and Seas—records of the sage-kings' deeds.' By this account, might not Bo Yi be the author? Yet the preface itself states: 'Yu distinguished the Nine Provinces; nothing escaped his gaze; thus he composed the Classic of Mountains and Seas.' These two accounts contradict each other—both confound the reader.

    There is yet another confusion. The Documents of Antiquity say: 'Yao put Gun to death at Feather Mountain'—because Gun's work in controlling the waters bore no success. Yet this Classic says: 'The Emperor slew Gun at Feather Field.' The 'Emperor' here refers to the Celestial Emperor on high. If Gun stole the Celestial Emperor's sacred soil, and yet truly succeeded in stopping the flood, then he would have merit before Yao but guilt before the Celestial Emperor. Why would Yao need to execute him when only the Celestial Emperor should? Conversely, if he was executed by the Celestial Emperor, then he never stole the sacred soil to dam the waters—so by what right would the Celestial Emperor kill him?

    These two accounts are incompatible. Which should we follow? Orthodox scholars would surely take the Documents as authoritative and regard the Classic of Mountains and Seas as wild fancy. Yet if we say Yu compiled it, how could Yu's own account seem so strange? Let us await a wise and discerning sage of later ages to resolve this confusion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gun (鯀) was Yu's father, a figure from Chinese mythology who attempted to control the Great Flood before Yu succeeded him.
  - key: ''
    value: The Classic of Mountains and Seas (Shanhaijing) is an ancient Chinese geographical text of disputed authorship and dating, traditionally attributed to Yu but now known to be a compilation from various sources.
  - key: ''
    value: Bo Yi and Bo Yue are legendary figures associated with early Chinese civilization and the classification of natural phenomena.
